12/26/22, 11:33 AM - Muskaan: // Online C compiler to run C program online
#include <stdio.h>
#include<string.h>
#include<stdlib.h>

struct car
{
    char model[30];
    int price;
    int fuel_type;
    union
    {
        struct{
            float bat_capacity;
            int range_in_km;
        }ev;
        struct {
            char fuel[20];
            int tank_capacity;
        }non_ev;
        
    }details;
};

void display_ev(struct car*,int);

void max_range_ev(struct car*,int);

struct car return_max_range_ev(struct car*,int);

int main() {
    // Write C code here
    struct car *c,temp;
    int n,i;
    printf("\n Enter the no.of cars: ");
    scanf("%d",&n);
    c=(struct car*)malloc(n*sizeof(struct car));
    if(c==NULL)
    {
        printf("\n Memory Allocation Failed!!");
        return 0;
    }
    
    fflush(stdin);
    for(i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        printf("\n Enter the model of car %d: ",i+1);
        
        fflush(stdin);
        gets((c+i)->model);
        fflush(stdin);
        puts((c+i)->model);
        printf("\n Enter price of car %d: ",i+1);
        scanf("%d",&(c+i)->price);
        fflush(stdin);
        printf("\n Enter 1 for EV and 2 for Non-EV");
        scanf("%d",&(c+i)->fuel_type);
        fflush(stdin);
        switch((c+i)->fuel_type)
        {
            case 1:
            printf("\n Enter Baterry Capacity: ");
            scanf("%f",&(c+i)->details.ev.bat_capacity);
            fflush(stdin);
            printf("\n Enter range: ");
            scanf("%d",&(c+i)->details.ev.range_in_km);
            fflush(stdin);
            
            break;
            
            case 2:
            printf("\n Enter Fuel: ");
            gets((c+i)->details.non_ev.fuel);
            fflush(stdin);
            printf("\n Tank Capacity: ");
            scanf("%d",&(c+i)->details.non_ev.tank_capacity);
            
            break;
            
            default:
            printf("\n Please enter valid values!!");
            i--;
            
        }
    }
    
    display_ev(c,n);
    temp = return_max_range_ev(c,n);
    puts(temp.model);

    return 0;
}

void display_ev(struct car *a,int size)
{
    int i;
    for(i=0;i<size;i++)
    {
        if((a+i)->fuel_type == 1)
        {
            puts((a+i)->model);
            printf("\n Price is %d",(a+i)->price);
            printf("\n range %d",(a+i)->details.ev.range_in_km);
        }
    }
    return;
}

void max_range_ev(struct car *a,int size)
{
    int i,max=0,index;
    for(i=0;i<size;i++)
    {
        if((a+i)->fuel_type == 1)
        {
            if((a+i)->details.ev.range_in_km>max)
            {
                max = (a+i)->details.ev.range_in_km;
                index = i;
            }
        }
    }
    puts((a+index)->model);
    printf("\n Price is %d",(a+index)->price);
    printf("\n range %d",(a+index)->details.ev.range_in_km);
    
    return;
}

struct car return_max_range_ev(struct car *a,int size)
{
    int i,max=0,index;
    for(i=0;i<size;i++)
    {
        if((a+i)->fuel_type == 1)
        {
            if((a+i)->details.ev.range_in_km>max)
            {
                max = (a+i)->details.ev.range_in_km;
                index = i;
            }
        }
        
        return a[index];
    }
}

3/12/23, 1:49 AM - Muskaan: Dear Colleagues,
Greetings from IIC, JIIT Noida!!

We are pleased to inform you that Institution’s Innovation Council of JIIT Noida is organizing *Poster Presentation of Innovations on March 14, 2023 (12:00 PM onwards)* . The event aims at providing space for young innovators to present their innovation
through poster presentation.

 *Details of the event:* 
1. This competition is to open to all students of JIIT.
2. All entries must be submitted via google form only.
3. Only one entry will be accepted from one student/group.
4. The event is in Online mode.

 *Evaluation criteria* :
Evaluation of the submitted poster entries will be done on the basis of novelty, originality, and relevancy. After the screening, selected ideas will be called for presentation.

 *Technical specifications* :
1. Participants are required to idea illustration as .jpeg/.png/pdf format only.
2. The idea of poster should be clear.
3. It can either be handmade or software created.
4. Idea should be unique. Please avoid plagiarism.
Themes:
•	Innovation Strategy
•	Smart Transportation 
•	Technological Developments
•	Scientific Developments
•	Green Innovation
•	Customer-focused Innovation
•	Corporate Innovation
•	Design Thinking
•	Innovation in Supply Chain Management
•	Innovation in Agriculture
•	Creativity and Innovation in Business
•	Biotechnological Innovation
•	Smart Healthcare Delivery
•	Innovative Robotics/AI
•	Any other area of innovation 

 *Submission Link* :  https://forms.gle/2EFBY6TXJctvushF6

Last date of submission is *March 13, 2023* .

We solicit participation from all of you. You are also requested to encourage students to participate in this event. Poster of the event is attached for your consideration. 

Thanks & Regards,
Institution’s Innovation Council Team, JIIT Noida

4/3/23, 4:37 PM - Aryan Gupta: “Ooo…ahhh….ouch…stop, stop, stop! please,” the corridors of my college reverberated with the cries of a *fairly manly* man as I approached *the* booth. He was of the physique of someone just a little less bulky than Mr. Olympia himself. Well,  keeping the creepy visuals of a *man crying from pain* aside,(coz let's just agree, we all have been brought up believing; such things; do not exist!), I looked at the very long queue of 5 men, waiting for their turn to (let's say) get devastated. Devastated, I myself joined the line. I was not frustrated by the fact that there were only five men waiting in line to feel the **menstrual pain**(at least a simulation of it!), which is too less anyways, but the fact that of these five, three were dragged by their girlfriends to do so, that got me perturbed. Now I don’t say that I am some activist that says ‘all men and women are equal’ which brought me here(without the sheer influence of my girlfriend) but two things.  First. I don’t have a uterus. That means I won’t actually ever be able to *feel* what a woman, does every month, five(approx) days in a row when they are on their period. And second, I believe that ‘women are superior to men’. 

I was lost in the hysteria of my own thoughts when I heard a girl, dangling on the right arm of some boy; presumably her dearest boyfri*end, shriek:* “Baby! Aaapki baari kb aayegi!”. Obviously, she was *not* excited about her boy’s turn. Obviously not! But the sad part is, the boy was not excited either. Alas! at the same moment, the crybaby’s turn was over and this girlfriend’s ****boyfriend**** was called to place the pads on the place. The machine operator, the girlfriend, and the boyfriend were happy in decreasing order. The lady operating the pain generator was really sweet, but her actions… not so much. On other days I am a poor observer but, I noticed one thing then and there. The increasing intensity of the cramps was directly proportional to the smile on the girlfriend’s face and inversely proportional to that on the boyfriend’s. The smile, however, did not have even a pinch of evil in it. It was ****not**** “I want to have him feel the ***********monthlies*********** pain”, but the smile was more like, “I am so proud of him, that he can bear so much pain”. I learned something new that day. Whatever you do there is in the list of ‘How to make your girl happy’, nothing will make her as contended as seeing her guy on this pain-inflecting-monster which was a machine that stimulated menstrual pain!

Next in line was this skeleton wrapped in the thinnest human skin god ever made. The last two boys were absolutely *******devastated******* by that pain-inflicting monster. Remember, how Mr. near Olympia was crying when bound in the tentacles of it? Just by the way he took his position in the torture chair, I knew he would not last more than a few seconds. After all the daily soap drama I just saw the previous couple enact, I couldn’t bear any more of it. So, I thought I would make friends with the folks around me, which included a couple that looked really mature, that was behind me, and a guy the same as my height. This man should have been in front of me. He was. I counted there were five. But now he wasn’t. Maybe he had gone for a nature’s call. Or maybe he had gone for once and for all. The atmosphere there was not friendly for light-hearted guys after all. Anyways, his sudden disappearance was not so much of a shock to me, looking at the condition of the previous two men. 

I was back on my track to *“making friends”* with the ******mature****** couple behind me. ten minutes or so on this track our collective chatter was broken by the lady operator’s commanding tone.

“Is the machine working fine?”, she one of the people assisting her. 

“It was, up until now this guy showed up!”, replied the assistant.

Well, it was, working well. Well? That sci-fi bot was working very well, absolutely killing every single man that entered its shrine, killing their male ego along with them!

After another good ten minutes of silence, following, pressing buttons of the machine in every possible permutation, the lady operator got contentment that the machine there is nothing wrong with the machine only by testing it on herself. (Which she did, with a straight face… trust me!). 

Bewildered the lady operator, tried the machine on the skinny sulky boy one last time, as if this time with a firm resolution that she will not condone him. But even her best tries to inflict any pain on this guy seem to fail. It felt as if this monster had itself braced this poor guy as if every one of his prayers came true. 

Removing the pads of the machine from the lower abdomen of the guy on the chair, the lady operator commented. “It is strong!”. Of course,  the machine is strong, I thought. So then how could it go out of order without even tweaking a single muscle of this flaky man, I continued to think.

“Either his lower abdomen is strong… or his willpower!”, exhaled the operator, as if consoling herself for the defeat of her dear *pain devil.* I learned another new thing that day, that each one of us is made differently, some feel more of it, and some feel it less. Or maybe I learned that the menstrual pain-generating machine acts weird sometimes. As I was making peace with the matter-of-fact words she just said, the skinny guy got up and walked off the scene as if nothing ever happened.

It was my turn next!

I was definitely nervous. I clearly remember but there is this itch inside me wanting to try new things, that made me sit on the seat of honor. My promptness in action to feel the pain, and seeing no girl next to me actually surprised the machine operator. As I said, this lady was a sweet lady. She gave me all the instructions to me, as to how to be safe during the process, again. But as I also said, this sweet lady’s actions were not all so sweet(Alas!). While setting up the pads of the machine on me, there was a familiar kind of smile I witnessed on her face. Of the kind that I saw earlier somewhere. 

“Don’t remove your hands from the pads no matter what, and DONT get up from the chair”, she said in a monotone. And then added, “even after we are done!”.  This felt like a warning more than an instruction.

Looking into my eyes, she started doing what she was here for - operating the machine. Commanding it to kill the hell out of all these fickle-minded men! 

First three seconds I felt nothing, but that nothingness was just the silence before the storm! 

(Ye teen seconds kaise beet gaye pta hi nhi chala)

Immediately after that, I felt something building up, below where the pads were. That something was a tickling sensation as if a small baby was punching you with its small hands. 

“I could feel it now”, I blurted out, struggling to maintain the calm in my voice.

And before I even had the time to register what was happening, get ticked by this *tickling sensation,* the vibrations in my belly grew so much it caused intense pain. And two holy words fell out of my mouth. 

“Holy… Shit…” I cried.

And it all went away as soon as it came. When I opened my eyes, I saw the sweet lady making some adjustments to the knobs of the machine. It was then I knew we were not done yet. I don’t know on what setting did she leave the machine then, but I do know this weird, abrupt, intense pain was now periodic. No cuss words, no logical justification, and not even the thought of god came into my mind at that moment. It was so painful. I could feel when my muscles were being contracted and relaxing, I could feel the sharp, poking, tightening one feels while a muscle cramp. All my best efforts to keep a straight face were no good, I was like 5-year-old throwing tantrums on not buying his new favorite toy. And after 40-50 seconds, which felt like 40-50 years in a dungeon, it all melted away. Nothing. I opened my eyes, hoping not to see this cruel lady ever again, only to find out, she was letting me breathe, before reaching the climax. 

“Now going to 80% power”, declared the sadist lady.

What! I couldn't believe my ears. What do you mean, ‘now going to 80’? I thought we have already surpassed 100. Another bout of two holy words fell off my mouth, this time 80% louder!

“HOLY SHIT!!!”

I was sweating, from head to toe, crying internally, ofc, (coz let's just agree, we all have been brought up believing; such things; do not exist!), I could feel my stomach trembling, that in turn was shaking my thigh; along with my entire belief system! 

It was when my left leg almost rose off the ground, a cruel lady(who was pretending to be sweet all this while) turned down the lever, and the stinging pain stopped. I opened my eyes looking in a direction away from the lady, or else another pair of holy words would have come out.
4/3/23, 4:37 PM - Aryan Gupta: (period)

What felt like an eternity, was literally three seconds, later, and this lady asked me to still be seated in my chair. As if I would have been able to get up. It all made sense now. It all made sense…

It made sense why are some girls absent on ************that day of the month************ every month. It made sense why do we order out, or mum stays in, when she has her ***************monthly cycles.*************** It made perfect sense, as to why there are pleas, in the Supreme Court, seeking menstrual pain leave for female students and working women. I made sense why Nikki Tajiri, the author of *She Dreams when she Bleeds,* wrote:

    “Men have shed blood in the battle 

     But all the blood they have shed is nothing 

     Compared to the women of the world!”

It all made sense.

I sat a boy, and got up, a man.

I will never be the same again!

7/18/23, 11:13 PM - Muskaan: vector <int> getSecondOrderElements(int n, vector <int> a) {
    // Write your code here.
        int slarge=0,ssmall=0;
        for(int i=0;i<=n-2;i++){
            int mini=i;
            for(int j=i;i<=n-1;j++){
                if(a[j]<a[mini]){
                    int temp=a[mini];
                    a[mini]=a[j];
                    a[j]=temp;
                }
            }
        }
        for(int k=n-2; k>=0;k--)
        {
            if(a[k]!=a[n-1])
            {
                slarge=a[k];
            }
            break;
        }
        for(int l=1; l<=n-1;l++)
        {
            if(a[l]!=a[0])
            {
                ssmall=a[l];
            }
            break;
        }
        return {slarge,ssmall};
}

7/19/23, 11:47 PM - Muskaan: pair<long long, long long> getMinMax(long long a[], int n) {
    int min,max;
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        min=a[0];
        max=a[0];
        if (a[i]<min)
        {
            min=a[i];
        }
        else if (a[i]>max)
        {
            max=a[i];
        }
    }
    return make_pair(min,max);
}

7/23/23, 10:52 PM - Muskaan: Muskaan: “Don’t let anyone rob you of your imagination, your creativity, or your curiosity. It’s your place in the world; it’s your life. Go on and do all you can with it, and make it the life you want to live.”

Manan : Warm greetings to fellow students, teachers and our esteemed speaker! Today I, Manan...

Muskaan : Along with I,Muskan are your hosts for today’s event!

Manan: But what is today's event about Muskan?

Muskaan: Today, we at IEEE Student Branch JIIT have a thrilling event organised in the celebration of WIE Day. 

Manan: The IEEE Women in Engineering is a global network of members and volunteers dedicated to promoting women in engineering and scientists, inspiring girls all over the world to become who they wish to be and break the stigmas set by society by following their academic interests.

Muskaan: Each year, the International WIE Day is celebrated on 23rd June. This year's theme for the WIE day focuses on Women's participation for lessening the ill-effects of climate change. 

Manan: Climate change and the hazards it can cause have been recorded everywhere in the world. As we work on saving the planet, we need to acknowledge the mistakes made in the past. 

Muskaan: The only way to survive and win this battle today is by recognizing that we as humans should all contribute to the cause. This directly links to letting each individual, man or woman, use their expertise as they work together, hand in hand, with mutual respect towards each other. 
 
Manan: Hence, we at IEEE have arranged a special webinar today, where we are joined by a woman in stem, facilitating an exceptional talk for all of us and enlightening us on the subject of Engaging Women in Mitigating Climate Change & Building Climate Resilience.

Muskaan:  We are honoured to have an extraordinary speaker among us, who has dedicated her life's work to environmental engineering and raising awareness about climate change. After completing her Bachelor's in Civil Engineering, she pursued her dreams further by specialising in Environmental Engineering during her Master's. She loves organising campaigns, workshops and programs to spread environmental awareness. Embodying sustainability is her lifestyle she firmly believes that small efforts can lead to big changes. Please welcome Ankita Patil ma’am, a committed advocate for mitigating climate change and a true inspiration for today's youth.


Manan : Ma’am, we thank you for taking out the time from your busy schedule to be present with us today. We request you to kindly throw some light on the subject and commence this event.

Muskaan: That was a very engaging and truly enlightening presentation! It perfectly captures the essence of the topic and gives us an understanding, as young engineers-to-be, a motivation to do better and be better towards our planet.  

Manan: I cannot agree more with Muskan. I would now like to open the panel to our fellow audience for a brief question and answer round. Please turn on your mics or write your questions in the chat box. 

Muskaan: On this note, we would like to end today's event. Once again we want to express our heartfelt gratitude to Ankita ma’am for joining us today and helping us celebrate the women in engineering. Thank you!

8/31/23, 1:16 PM - Muskaan: from collections import Counter

# Read the content of the file
with open("student.txt", "r") as file:
    content = file.read()

# Split the content into words
words = content.split()

# Count the frequency of each word
word_frequency = Counter(words)

# Create a dictionary sorted by word frequency
sorted_dict = dict(sorted(word_frequency.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))

print(sorted_dict)
8/31/23, 1:16 PM - Muskaan: <Media omitted>
8/31/23, 1:16 PM - Muskaan: def decode_string(encoded_string):
    decoded_string = ""
    i = 0
    while i < len(encoded_string):
        if encoded_string[i] == '#':
            count = int(encoded_string[i+1])
            char = encoded_string[i+2]
            decoded_string += char * count
            i += 3
        else:
            decoded_string += encoded_string[i]
            i += 1
    return decoded_string

# List of encoded strings
encoded_strings = ["#3A#5GER", "#2H#4I#2J"]

# Decoding the strings and creating a list of decoded strings
decoded_strings = [decode_string(encoded) for encoded in encoded_strings]

print(decoded_strings)

9/27/23, 10:06 AM - Aryan Gupta: Server side

#include<stdio.h>

#include<string.h> //strlen

#include<sys/socket.h>

#include<arpa/inet.h> //inet_addr


int main(int argc , char *argv[])

{

int socket_desc;

struct sockaddr_in server;

char *message , server_reply[2000];


//Create socket

socket_desc = socket(AF_INET , SOCK_STREAM , 0);

if (socket_desc == -1)

{

printf("Could not create socket");

}


server.sin_addr.s_addr = inet_addr("74.125.235.20");

server.sin_family = AF_INET;

server.sin_port = htons( 80 );


//Connect to remote server

if (connect(socket_desc , (struct sockaddr *)&server , sizeof(server)) < 0)

{

puts("connect error");

return 1;

}


puts("Connected\n");


//Send some data

message = "GET / HTTP/1.1\r\n\r\n";

if( send(socket_desc , message , strlen(message) , 0) < 0)

{

puts("Send failed");

return 1;

}

puts("Data Send\n");


//Receive a reply from the server

if( recv(socket_desc, server_reply , 2000 , 0) < 0)

{

puts("recv failed");

}

puts("Reply received\n");

puts(server_reply);


return 0;

}


close(socket_desc);




Client side


#include<stdio.h>

#include<sys/socket.h>

#include<arpa/inet.h> //inet_addr


int main(int argc , char *argv[])

{

int socket_desc , new_socket , c;

struct sockaddr_in server , client;


//Create socket

socket_desc = socket(AF_INET , SOCK_STREAM , 0);

if (socket_desc == -1)

{

printf("Could not create socket");

}


//Prepare the sockaddr_in structure

server.sin_family = AF_INET;

server.sin_addr.s_addr = INADDR_ANY;

server.sin_port = htons( 8888 );


//Bind

if( bind(socket_desc,(struct sockaddr *)&server , sizeof(server)) < 0)

{

puts("bind failed");

}

puts("bind done");


//Listen

listen(socket_desc , 3);


//Accept and incoming connection

puts("Waiting for incoming connections...");

c = sizeof(struct sockaddr_in);

new_socket = accept(socket_desc, (struct sockaddr *)&client, (socklen_t*)&c);

if (new_socket<0)

{

perror("accept failed");

}


puts("Connection accepted");


return 0;

}




//Reply to the client

message = "Hello Client , I have received your connection. But I have to go now, bye\n";

write(new_socket , message , strlen(message));



Live Server

#include<string.h> //strlen

#include<sys/socket.h>

#include<arpa/inet.h> //inet_addr

#include<unistd.h> //write


int main(int argc , char *argv[])

{

int socket_desc , new_socket , c;

struct sockaddr_in server , client;

char *message;


//Create socket

socket_desc = socket(AF_INET , SOCK_STREAM , 0);

if (socket_desc == -1)

{

printf("Could not create socket");

}


//Prepare the sockaddr_in structure

server.sin_family = AF_INET;

server.sin_addr.s_addr = INADDR_ANY;

server.sin_port = htons( 8888 );


//Bind

if( bind(socket_desc,(struct sockaddr *)&server , sizeof(server)) < 0)

{

puts("bind failed");

return 1;

}

puts("bind done");


//Listen

listen(socket_desc , 3);


//Accept and incoming connection

puts("Waiting for incoming connections...");

c = sizeof(struct sockaddr_in);

while( (new_socket = accept(socket_desc, (struct sockaddr *)&client, (socklen_t*)&c)) )

{

puts("Connection accepted");


//Reply to the client

message = "Hello Client , I have received your connection. But I have to go now, bye\n";

write(new_socket , message , strlen(message));

}


if (new_socket<0)

{

perror("accept failed");

return 1;

}


return 0;

}

9/28/23, 8:53 AM - Aryan Gupta: #include <stdio.h>
Int main ()
{
  printf ("---PRIORITY SCHEDULING ALGORITHM--- \n");
  int n;
  printf ("ENTER THE NO. OF PROCESS: ");
  scanf ("%d", &n);
 
  int id[n];
  int pri[n];
  int bust[n];
 
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
	{
  	printf ("Enter the burst time and priority of process id %d : ", i);
  	int b, p;
  	scanf ("%d%d", &b, &p);
     	pri[i] = p;
  	bust[i] = b;
  	id[i] = i;
	}
 
  //sorting each process according to their priority
  for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++)
   {
  	for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++)
  	{
        	
        	     if (pri[i] < pri[j])  	//considering higher the number higher the priority
        	     {
        	   
        	   	int temp_b = bust[i], temp_ = pri[i], temp_i = id[i];
        	   	bust[i] = bust[j];
        	   	pri[i] = pri[j];
        	   	id[i] = id[j];
        	     
        	   	bust[i]=bust[j];
       	pri[i]=pri[j];
       	id[i]=id[j];
        	     }
   	}
 	}
 
  int time=0;  //for peinting gantt chart in same line
  printf("GANTT CHART \n |%d| ",time);
  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  {
  	time+=bust[i];
  	printf("process_id=%d |%d|",id[i],time);
  }
  printf("\n");
  time=0;  //now printing the process table with TAT and WT of each process
  printf("processid  turn_around_time waiting_time\n");
  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  {
  	printf("   	%d             	%d       	%d\n",id[i],time+bust[i],time);
  	time+=bust[i];
  }
 
}

#include <stdio.h>
 
int main ()
{
  printf ("---SJF SCHEDULING ALGORITHM--- \n");
  int n;
  printf ("ENTER THE NO. OF PROCESS: ");
  scanf ("%d", &n);
 
  int id[n];
  int bust[n];
 
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
	{
  	printf ("Enter the burst time of process id %d : ", i);
  	int b, p;
  	scanf ("%d", &b);
  	bust[i] = b;
  	id[i] = i;
	}
 
  //sorting each process according to the shortest burst time
  for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++)
   {
  	for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++)
  	{
        	
        	     if (bust[i] > bust[j]) //if the bsut time of pro at i is greater
        	                       	//than that of pro at j then we will swap bith of them
        	     {
        	   
        	   	int temp_b = bust[i],temp_i = id[i];
        	   	bust[i] = bust[j];
        	   	id[i] = id[j];
        	     
        	   	bust[j]=temp_b;
       	id[j]=temp_i;
        	     }
   	}
 	}
 
  int time=0;  //for printing gantt chart in same line
  printf("GANTT CHART \n |%d| ",time);
  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  {
  	time+=bust[i];
  	printf("process_id=%d |%d|",id[i],time);
  }
  printf("\n");
  time=0;  //now printing the process table with TAT and WT of each process
  printf("processid  turn_around_time waiting_time\n");
  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  {
  	printf("   	%d             	%d       	%d\n",id[i],time+bust[i],time);
  	time+=bust[i];
  }
}

#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdbool.h>
int main ()
{
  printf ("---ROUND ROBIN SCHEDULING ALGORITHM--- \n");
  int n;
  int quant;
  printf ("ENTER THE NO. OF PROCESS: ");
  scanf ("%d", &n);
  printf("ENTER THE TIME QUANTUM TAKEN: ");
  scanf("%d",&quant);
 
  int id[n];
  int bust[n];
 
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
	{
  	printf ("Enter the burst time of process id %d : ", i);
  	int b;
  	scanf ("%d", &b);
  	bust[i] = b;
  	id[i] = i;
	}
 
 
  int time=0;
  int rem_bust[n];
  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  {
  	rem_bust[i]=bust[i];
  }
 
  printf("GANTT CHART \n |%d|",time);
 
  bool flag = true;
 
  while(flag)
  {
  	flag = false;
  	for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  	{
      	if(rem_bust[i]>0)
      	{
          	if(rem_bust[i]<quant)
          	{
              	time+=rem_bust[i];
              	printf("process_id=%d |%d|", id[i],time);
                  rem_bust[i]-=rem_bust[i];  //that is make it zero to mwwr the if cond
                                             //stated above
          	}
          	else
         	 {
              	time+=quant;
              	printf("process_id=%d |%d|",id[i],time);
              	rem_bust[i]-=quant;
          	}
          	flag= true;
      	}
  	}
  }
}

9/28/23, 8:53 AM - Aryan Gupta: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <pthread.h>

struct process{
	int bust;
	int ari;
	int avl;
	int id;
	int r_bust;
	int p_ari;
	int turn;
	int ca;
	int pri;
};



int * n;
int*t1;
int*t2;
struct process *p;

void * fcfs (void * arg)
{
	for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
	{
		for(int j=0;j<*n;j++)
		{
			if(p[i].ari<p[j].ari)
			{
				struct process t  = p[i];
				p[i] = p[j];
				p[j] = t;
			}
		}
	}

	int time =0;
	int count =0;
	printf("GANT CHART\n|%d| ",time);
	while(count<*n)
	{
		int flag =0;
		for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
		{
			if(p[i].p_ari<=time && p[i].r_bust>0)
			{
				p[i].avl=1;
				flag=1;
			}
			else p[i].avl=0;
		}
		if(flag==1)
		{
			for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
			{
				if(p[i].avl==1)
				{
					time+=p[i].r_bust;
					printf(" process %d |%d| ",p[i].id,time);
					p[i].r_bust-=p[i].r_bust;
					p[i].ca=time;
					count++;
				}
			}
		}
		else
		{
			time+=1;
			printf(" |%d| ",time);
		}
	}
	printf("\n");

}

void * prior (void * arg)
{
	for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
	{
		for(int j=0;j<*n;j++)
		{
			if(p[i].ari<p[j].ari)
			{
				struct process t  = p[i];
				p[i] = p[j];
				p[j] = t;
			}
		}
	}

	int time =0;
	int count =0;
	printf("GANT CHART\n|%d| ",time);
	while(count<*n)
	{
		int flag =0;
		int index = 0;
		for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
		{
			if(p[i].p_ari<=time && p[i].r_bust>0)
			{
				p[i].avl=1;
				flag=1;
				index = i;
			}
			else p[i].avl=0;
		}
		if(flag==1)
		{
			
			for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
			{
				if(p[i].avl==1 && p[index].pri<p[i].pri)
				{
					index = i;
				}
			}
			
			time +=1;
			printf(" process %d |%d| ",p[index].id,time);
			p[index].r_bust-=1;
			if(p[index].r_bust==0)
			{
				count++;
				p[index].ca=time;
			}
			
		}
		else
		{
			time+=1;
			printf(" |%d| ",time);
		}
	}
	printf("\n");

}

void * round_robin(void * arg)
{
	for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
	{
		for(int j=0;j<*n;j++)
		{
			if(p[i].ari<p[j].ari)
			{
				struct process t  = p[i];
				p[i] = p[j];
				p[j] = t;
			}
		}
	}

	int time =0;
	int count =0;
	printf("GANT CHART\n|%d| ",time);
	while(count<*n)
	{
		int flag =0;
		for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
		{
			if(p[i].p_ari<=time && p[i].r_bust>0)
			{
				p[i].avl=1;
				flag=1;
			}
			else p[i].avl=0;
		}
		if(flag==1)
		{
			for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
			{
				if(p[i].avl==1)
				{
					if(p[i].r_bust<=(*t1))
					{
						time+=p[i].r_bust;
						printf(" process %d |%d| ",p[i].id,time);
						p[i].r_bust=0;
						p[i].ca=time;
						count++;
					}
					else
					{
						time+=(*t1);
						printf(" process %d |%d| ",p[i].id,time);
						p[i].r_bust-=(*t1);
						p[i].p_ari=time;
					}
				}
				
			}
			
			for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
			{
				for(int j=0;j<*n;j++)
				{
					if((p[i].p_ari<p[j].p_ari) || (p[i].p_ari==p[j].p_ari && p[i].ari<p[j].ari))
					{
						struct process t  = p[i];
						p[i] = p[j];
						p[j] = t;
					}

				}
			}
			
		}
		else
		{
			time+=1;
			printf(" |%d| ",time);
		}
	}
	printf("\n");

}


void * display(void *arr)
{
	printf("pid at bt ca ta wt\n");
	for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
	{
		for(int j=0;j<*n;j++)
		{
			if(p[i].id<p[j].id)
			{
				struct process l = p[i];
				p[i] = p[j];
				p[j] = l;
			}
		}
	}
	for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
	{
		printf(" %d  %d %d %d %d %d\n",p[i].id,p[i].ari,p[i].bust,p[i].ca,p[i].ca-p[i].ari,p[i].ca-p[i].ari-p[i].bust);
	}
}

	 t1 = malloc(sizeof(int));

	 pthread_t tt1,tt2;
	for(int i=0;i<*n;i++)
	{

		scanf("%d%d",&b,&a);

		p[i].p_ari=a;

	pthread_create(&tt1,NULL,round_robin,NULL);
	pthread_join(tt1,NULL);
	pthread_create(&tt2,NULL,display,NULL);

11/9/23, 7:49 PM - Aryan Gupta: In a tranquil village school, there are two students named Ramu and Sonu, each possessing a collection of
N distinct chalks. Each student's chalks are of different lengths, represented by N positive integers. Ramu
has arranged his collection of N chalks in a specific order based on their lengths. Sonu is eager to organize
his own N chalks in a way that mimics Ramu's arrangement in terms of length changes i.e. if in Ramu's
arrangement the kth chalk is bigger than the (k+l)th chalk, in Sonu's arrangement also the kth chalk will be
bigger than the (k+l)th chalk; alternately if it is smaller in Ramu's arrangement, then it will be smaller in
Sonu's as well.
Sonu was busy arranging his chalks, when his teacher told him to also maximize the overall "niceness" of
his arrangement. Here, 'niceness' is defined as the sum of the absolute length differences between all
adjacent chalks in the arrangement.
Write a program to assist Sonu in achieving both the objectives: first, to mimic Ramu's length variation
order, and second, to maximize the overall niceness of the arrangement.
Read the input from STDIN and print the output to STDOUT. Do not write arbitrary strings anywhere in the
program, as these contribute to the standard output, and test cases will fail.

Constraints:
2 <= N <= 10000
2 <= Chalk length <= 10000

Input Format:
The first line of the input consists of the integer N, representing the number of chalks each student has.
The second line contains N distinct positive integers, which is Ramu's arrangement of his chalks, each
represented by its length.
The third line comprises N distinct positive integers, which is Sonu's chalk collection.
Output Format:
Single line of the output should display the maximum achievable niceness resulting from the arrangement
of Sonu's chalk collection to mimic Ramu's chalk arrangement.


Sample Inputl:
4
5 7 4 9
1 2 3 4
Sample Output 1:
7

Explanationl:
Given N = 4.
Ramu's chalks are arranged in the order of their length as 5 7 4 9, which corresponds to an increase-
decrease-increase pattern of arrangement.
Sonu has the chalk collection 1 2 3 4.
To mimic Ramu's chalk arrangement order of increase-decrease-increase, Sonu can arrange his chalk in
the following five ways.
- niceness-> |1-3|+|3-2|+|2-4| = 2+1+2=5
- niceness-> |1-4|+|4-2|+|2-3| = 3+2+1=6
- niceness-> |2-3|+|3-1|+|1-4| = 1+2+3=6
- niceness-> |2-4|+|4-1|+|1-3| = 2+3+2=7
- niceness-> |3-4|+|4-1|+|1-2| = 1+3+1=5
As can be seen, the maximum niceness possible is 7, which is printed as output.

Sample Input2:
5
12 13 14 15 16
23 34 45 44 33
Sample Output2:
22
Explanation2:
Given, N = 5.
Ramu's chalks are arranged in the order of their length as 12 13 14 15 16, which corresponds to an
ascending pattern.
Sonu has the chalk collection 23 34 45 44 33 which can be arranged in an ascending order as:
{23, 33, 34, 44, 45} - niceness 10+1+10+1 = 22
So the output is 22.

11/9/23, 7:51 PM - Muskaan: Konsi language mein
11/9/23, 7:52 PM - Muskaan: #include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>
#include <vector>
#include <cmath>

using namespace std;

int maximizeNiceness(int N, vector<int>& ramuChalks, vector<int>& sonuChalks) {
    sort(sonuChalks.begin(), sonuChalks.end());

    int niceness = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        niceness += abs(ramuChalks[i] - sonuChalks[i]);
    }

    return niceness;
}

int main() {
    int N;
    cin >> N;

    vector<int> ramuChalks(N);
    vector<int> sonuChalks(N);

    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        cin >> ramuChalks[i];
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
        cin >> sonuChalks[i];
    }

    int result = maximizeNiceness(N, ramuChalks, sonuChalks);
    cout << result << endl;

    return 0;
}
11/9/23, 7:58 PM - Muskaan: A double-ended queue (shortened as 'deque') has the following operations which can be implemented on
it:
PUSH X: Adds the element X to the back of the deque.
POP: Removes an element from the back of the deque.
INJECT X : Adds the element X to the front of the deque.
EJECT: Removes an element from the front of the deque. 
SHOW: Print all the popped elements and stop accepting further inputs.

Write a program that accepts a set of operations as input, and prints the elements that are popped from the deque.
Read the input from STDIN and print the output to STDOUT. Do not print arbitrary strings anywhere in the
program, as these contribute to the standard output and test cases will fail.
Constraints:
The elements of the deque are all integers.
Input Format:
The input will be the operations, one in each line.
All operations (PUSH, POP, INJECT, EJECT, SHOW) will always be in upper case.
PUSH and INJECT operations will always be accompanied by a single integer.
SHOW will be the last line of input.
Output Format:
The output will be the elements that are popped from the deque, each separated by a single whitespace.
Print "Empty" (use exact case) if no element exists in the deque at the time of popping.
PUSH 5
PUSH 11
POP
INJECT 8
EJECT
PUSH 9
SHOW
Sample Output:
11
sample-lnput
INJECT 1
EJECT
POP
INJECT 65
PUSH 23458
POP
SHOW
Sample Output2:
Empty 23458
11/9/23, 7:58 PM - Muskaan: #include <iostream>
#include <deque>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    deque<int> dq;
    string operation;
    int num;

    while (true) {
        cin >> operation;

        if (operation == "PUSH") {
            cin >> num;
            dq.push_back(num);
        } else if (operation == "POP") {
            if (!dq.empty()) {
                cout << dq.back() << " ";
                dq.pop_back();
            } else {
                cout << "Empty ";
            }
        } else if (operation == "INJECT") {
            cin >> num;
            dq.push_front(num);
        } else if (operation == "EJECT") {
            if (!dq.empty()) {
                cout << dq.front() << " ";
                dq.pop_front();
            } else {
                cout << "Empty ";
            }
        } else if (operation == "SHOW") {
            break;
        }
    }

    return 0;
}

11/23/23, 10:28 AM - Muskaan: You are tasked with stimulating a disk scheduling scenario on a computer system. The disk has 200 tracks numbered from 0 to 199. A disk scheduling algorithm needs to be implemented to efficiently handle a queue of disk requests.

Disk request queue:
98,183,37,122,14,124,65,67
Starting head position : head starts at track 53
Tasks: write a program to apply the FCFS disk scheduling algorithm to the given disk request queue. Calculate the total head movement and the order in which requests are serviced.
11/23/23, 10:28 AM - Muskaan: Apply the scan disk scheduling algorithm to the same disk request queue, moving towards the end of the disk ( right). Calculate the total head movement and the order in which requests are serviced.
11/23/23, 10:28 AM - Muskaan: Sure, I can guide you through both FCFS (First-Come-First-Serve) and SCAN disk scheduling algorithms for the given scenario.

### FCFS Disk Scheduling Algorithm:

1. **Initialize:**
   - Disk queue: 98, 183, 37, 122, 14, 124, 65, 67
   - Head position: 53

2. **Calculate Head Movements:**
   - Iterate through the queue in the order they appear.
   - Calculate the absolute difference between the current head position and the next request.
   - Accumulate the differences to get the total head movement.

3. **Order of Service:**
   - Requests are serviced in the order they appear in the queue.

### SCAN Disk Scheduling Algorithm:

1. **Initialize:**
   - Disk queue: 98, 183, 37, 122, 14, 124, 65, 67
   - Head position: 53
   - Disk size: 200 tracks

2. **Sort the Disk Queue:**
   - Sort the disk queue in ascending order.

3. **Calculate Head Movements:**
   - Move the head towards the end of the disk while serving requests in the sorted order.
   - When reaching the end, reverse direction and continue serving requests until reaching the other end.
   - Calculate the absolute difference between the current head position and the next request.
   - Accumulate the differences to get the total head movement.

4. **Order of Service:**
   - Requests are serviced based on the SCAN algorithm, moving towards the end and then reversing.

Feel free to implement these steps in your preferred programming language, and let me know if you have any specific questions or need further assistance!
11/23/23, 10:28 AM - Muskaan: def fcfs_scheduling(queue, head_position):
    total_head_movement = 0
    order_of_service = []

    for request in queue:
        total_head_movement += abs(head_position - request)
        order_of_service.append(request)
        head_position = request

    return total_head_movement, order_of_service


def scan_scheduling(queue, head_position, disk_size):
    total_head_movement = 0
    order_of_service = []

    sorted_queue = sorted(queue)

    # Move towards the end
    for request in sorted_queue:
        if request >= head_position:
            total_head_movement += abs(head_position - request)
            order_of_service.append(request)
            head_position = request

    # Move towards the other end
    total_head_movement += abs(head_position - disk_size)
    order_of_service.append(disk_size)
    head_position = disk_size

    for request in sorted_queue[::-1]:
        if request < head_position:
            total_head_movement += abs(head_position - request)
            order_of_service.append(request)
            head_position = request

    return total_head_movement, order_of_service


# Given scenario
disk_queue = [98, 183, 37, 122, 14, 124, 65, 67]
initial_head_position = 53
disk_size = 200

# FCFS
fcfs_movement, fcfs_order = fcfs_scheduling(disk_queue, initial_head_position)
print(f"FCFS Total Head Movement: {fcfs_movement}")
print(f"FCFS Order of Service: {fcfs_order}")

# SCAN
scan_movement, scan_order = scan_scheduling(disk_queue, initial_head_position, disk_size)
print(f"SCAN Total Head Movement: {scan_movement}")
print(f"SCAN Order of Service: {scan_order}")

12/20/23, 1:45 AM - Aryan Gupta: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    while(t--) {
        int sum=0,x;
        string keyboard,sentence;
        cin>>keyboard>>sentence;
        int start = keyboard.find(sentence[0]);
        for(int i=1;i<sentence.size();i++) {
            x= (keyboard.find(sentence[i])-keyboard.find(sentence[i-1]));
            if(x<0) {
                x*=-1;
            }
            sum = sum + x;
        } 
        cout<<sum<<endl;
    }
    return 0;
}

12/21/23, 1:45 AM - Aryan Gupta: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
 
int main()
{
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    int n;
    string s1,s2;
    while(t--) {
        cin>>n;
        cin>>s1>>s2;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++) {
            if(s1[i]=='G') {
                s1[i]='B';
            }
            if(s2[i]=='G') {
                s2[i]='B';
            }
        }
        if(s1==s2) {
            cout<<"YES"<<endl;
        }
        else {
            cout<<"NO"<<endl;
        }
    }
    return 0;
}

12/22/23, 1:30 AM - Aryan Gupta: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int temp;
    cin>>temp;
    int year=temp;
    int rem;
    for(int i= year+1;i<=9013;i++) {
        // cout<<"entered while loop"<<endl;
        // cout<<"new year is: "<<i<<endl;
        // year= year+1;
        int count=0;
        unordered_set<int> se;
        temp=i;
        while(temp>0) {
            rem=temp%10;
            se.insert(rem);
            temp=temp/10;
        }
        // cout<<"elements in set: "<<endl;
        for(auto it:se) {
            count++;
            // cout<<it<<" "<<endl;
        }
        // cout<<count<<endl;
        if(count==4) {
            // cout<<"check completed, entered if"<<endl;
            cout<<i;
            break;
        }
        // else {
            
        // }
        // cout<<"came out of if condition"<<endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

2/20/24, 8:33 PM - Muskaan: #include <iostream>

using namespace std;

 

class Node

{

public:

int data;

Node *next;

 

Node(int x)

{

     data = x;

     next = NULL;

}

};

 

class LL

{

Node *head;

Node *end;

int count;

public:

LL()

{

     head = NULL;

     end = NULL;

     count = 0;

}

addNodeBeg(int x)

{

     Node *n = new Node(x);

     if(count == 0)

     {

         head = n;

         end = n;

     }

     else

     {

         n->next = head;

         head = n;

     }

     count++;

}

addNodeEnd(int x)

{

     Node *n = new Node(x);

     if(count == 0)

     {

         head = end = n;

     }

     else

     {

         end->next = n;

         end = n;

     }

     count++;

}

addNodePos(int x, int y)

{

     if(count<y)

     {

         cout << "Position Out of Bound" << endl;

     }

     else

     {

         Node *n = new Node(x);

 

         if(y==0)

         {

             n->next = head;

             head = n;

         }

         else

         {

             Node *current = head;

             for(int i=0; i<y-1; i++)

                {

                 current=current->next;

             }

             n->next = current->next;

             current->next = n;

         }

     }

}

 

displayLL()

{

     Node *n = head;

     if(head==NULL)

     {

         cout << "LL is Empty";

     }

     while(n!= NULL)

     {

         cout << n->data;

         cout << " [" << n << "] ->";

         cout << n->next << endl;

         n=n->next;

     }

}

2/26/24, 11:33 PM - Aryan Gupta: clear all;
clc;
%ARYAN GUPTA 21104031
Sn = [1 0 0 0 1 1];
Rn = [0 0 1 0 0 1];
for i=1:6
    if Sn(i)==1
        if Rn(i)==0
            Q(i) = 1;
        end
    else
        if Rn(i)==0
            Q(i) = Q(i-1);
        else
            Q(i) = 0;
        end
    end
end 
Y=[Sn' Rn' Q'];
disp('Realization of SR Latch');
disp('----------------------')
disp('     Sn    Rn   Q(n+1) ')
disp(Y)
disp('----------------------')
disp('                         ')
disp('                         ')
Jn = [1 0 0 1 1 0 0 0];
Kn = [0 1 0 1 1 1 1 0];
clk = [1 1 1 1 0 0 1 1];
for i=1:8
    if clk(i)==1
        if Jn(i)==1
            if Kn(i)==0
                Q1(i) = 1;
            else
                Q1(i) = ~(Q1(i-1));
            end
        else
            if Kn(i)==0
                Q1(i)=Q1(i-1);
            else 
                Q1(i)=0;
            end
        end
    else
        Q1(i) = Q1(i-1);
    end
end
Z=[clk' Jn' Kn' Q1'];
disp('Realization of JK Latch');
disp('------------------------------')
disp('    clk    Jn    Kn    Q1(n+1) ')
disp(Z)
disp('------------------------------')
disp('                         ')
disp('                         ')
clock = [1 0 0 1 0 0 1];
Dn = [1 1 0 0 0 1 1];
for i=1:7
    if clock(i)==1
        if Dn(i)==1
            Q2(i)=1;
        else
            Q2(i)=0;
        end
    else
        Q2(i)=Q2(i-1);
    end
end
X=[clock' Dn' Q2'];
disp('Realization of D Latch');
disp('-----------------------')
disp('  clock    Dn   Q2(n+1) ')
disp(X)
disp('-----------------------')

% Muskaan Singhal 22103192
Sn = [0 0 1 1];
Rn = [0 1 0 1];
Q = zeros(1,4);
for i = 1:4
    if Sn(i) == 1
        if Rn(i) == 0
            Q(i) = 1;
        else
            Q(i) = 0;
        end
    elseif Rn(i) == 0
        Q(i) = Q(i-1);
    end
end
Y = [Sn' Rn' Q'];
disp('Realization of SR Latch');
disp('----------------------')
disp('     Sn    Rn   Q(n+1) ')
disp(Y)
disp('----------------------')
disp('                         ')
disp('                         ')
clock = [0 0 1 1];
Dn = [0 1 0 1];
Q2 = zeros(1,4);
for i = 1:4
    if i == 1 || clock(i) == 1
        if Dn(i) == 1
            Q2(i) = 1;
        else
            Q2(i) = 0;
        end
    else
        Q2(i) = Q2(i-1);
    end
end
X = [clock' Dn' Q2'];
disp('Realization of D Latch');
disp('-----------------------')
disp('  clock    Dn   Q2(n+1) ')
disp(X)
disp('-----------------------')

4/13/24, 12:23 AM - Muskaan: int sumOfAllDivisors(int n){
	// Write your code here.	
	int sum=0;
	for(int i=1;i<=n;i++)
	{
		for(int j=1;j<=sqrt(i);j++)
		{
			if(i%j==0)
			{
				if(j!=i/j){sum=sum+j+i/j;}
				else{sum=sum+j;}
			}
		}
	}
	return sum;
}
4/13/24, 12:24 AM - Muskaan: O(sqrt(n)) time complexity mein hi krne ko kaha h it passes 30/31 and woh aise 1 test case toh nhi dikhata so kya dikkat h code mein <This message was edited>

4/23/24, 12:00 AM - Muskaan: Given an array nums containing n distinct numbers in the range [0, n], return the only number in the range that is missing from the array.

 

Example 1:

Input: nums = [3,0,1]
Output: 2
Explanation: n = 3 since there are 3 numbers, so all numbers are in the range [0,3]. 2 is the missing number in the range since it does not appear in nums.
4/23/24, 12:00 AM - Muskaan: class Solution {
public:
    int missingNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
    int n=nums.size();
    vector<int> hash={0};
    int missing;
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        hash[nums[i]]+=1;
    }   
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        if(hash[i]==0)
        {
            missing=i;
        }
    }
    return missing;
    }
};
